<?php $__env->startSection('content'); ?><p>For years, Margaret Thatcher’s portrait has been the only one of a woman to adorn the famous yellow staircase at 10 Downing Street.</p>

<p>But yesterday, it was finally joined by a photo of Theresa May, the country’s second woman prime minister.</p>

<p>Portraits of former prime ministers line the staircase chronologically, so Mrs May is positioned next to her predecessor David Cameron.</p>

<p>For years, Margaret Thatcher’s portrait has been the only one of a woman to adorn the famous yellow staircase at 10 Downing Street. But yesterday, it was finally joined by a photo of Theresa May, the country’s second woman prime minister</p>

<p>Portraits of former prime ministers line the staircase chronologically, so Mrs May is positioned next to her predecessor David Cameron. Once a PM is out of office, his or her photo is added to the No.10 wall</p>

<p>Once a prime minister is out of office, his or her photo is added to the wall, then all the other pictures are shuffled down the staircase. </p>

<p>Art historian Simon Schama once said in a documentary on Downing Street: ‘Where you might have in other great houses of state, even in the White House, huge portraits, larger than life size, here [in the UK] we have modest engravings and photographs of the ghosts of Downing Street.’</p>
